    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Our recent observations of z~7 galaxies have demonstrated the
capability of ALMA in detecting the galaxies that formed in
the early Universe and contributed to the reionation process. Indeed we
detected the [CII]158 micron emission line in a z=7.109 galaxy, previously
confirmed from the presence of Lyalpha emission, with a  star formation
rate that does not exceed 8 Msun/yr.
This early success contrasts with the frustrating difficulties in 
measuring redshifts for large samples of LBGs at z&gt;6.5 with optical-near IR spectrographs, even with long integration times.
This is due to the fact that the Lyalpha emission line is often absent,
probably due to the increasing absorption of the IGM.
The goal of this proposal is to show that ALMA can be used as a powerful
machine to measure redshifts for the population of LBG at z &gt;6.5.
From the CANDELS UDS field we have selected a unique object at z~6.45 where Ly-alpha is absent but we have a good estimate of the redshifts, combining informations from CANDELS photometry and our deep VLT spectra. 
We show that we can detect the [CII]158Î¼m line from this galaxy, and hence demonstrate that ALMA can open a new window on the high redshift Universe.
</prp:abstract>
